  "draft_answer": "- ML-DSA includes a \"pre-hash\" variant (HashML-DSA) where messages are pre-hashed before signing, while ML-KEM is a key-encapsulation mechanism without such pre-hashing steps [c1][c3].  \n- ML-DSA signing involves a context string (max 255 bytes) and a hash function/XOF for pre-hashing, whereas ML-KEM focuses on key exchange without context parameters [c1][c3].  \n- HashML-DSA requires signature identifiers to specify the hash/XOF used, while ML-KEM does not involve signature identifiers or pre-hashing [c3].  \n- ML-KEM’s key generation and encapsulation/decapsulation processes are defined in FIPS 203, distinct from ML-DSA’s signing/verification algorithms [c4][c6].  \n- ML-DSA’s verification algorithm (HashML-DSA.Verify) explicitly checks context length, a feature absent in ML-KEM’s specifications [c2][c3].",
